paratory sehools and colleges, and itis believed to combine excellences of diverse kinds in such a way as to be the closest possible approach to an ideal grammar.

1. This has always been regarded as the truest and soundest of Latin grammar manuals. Instead of making arbitrary laws and distinctions in order to secure an artificial clearness of state- ment, this grammar has been faithful to the spirit and the facts of the language. This is its fundamental excellence. The grammar explains the language instead of trying to make the , language hear out the grammar. *¹

2. The present edition is as strong in class-room avallability as it is for linguistic truth. Mr. George L.
